	<Title>
		Natural treatments: Can you spot a fraud?
	</Title>
	<Body>
		&lt;p&gt;If something sounds too good to be true, it probably is. To spot potentially fraudulent herbal products or other &quot;natural&quot; treatments, look for these warning signs: 1. Promotional material includes words such as &quot;miracle cure&quot; or &quot;revolutionary discovery.&quot; 2. The manufacturer claims that the product can treat a wide range of symptoms, or cure or prevent a variety of diseases. 3. The product claims to &quot;purify,&quot; &quot;detoxify&quot; or &quot;energize.&quot; These terms may sound impressive and may even have an element of truth, but they&apos;re generally used to cover up a lack of scientific proof.&lt;/p&gt;
	</Body>
